I found a solution: don't use ModelFieldList and ModelForm on the top level form.
```
class BreakfastEggsForm(Form):
    eggs = FieldList(FormField(EggForm))
```
Normal FieldList works just fine.
It also works with a second layer of related objects, say spices related to an egg:
```
class SpiceForm(ModelForm):
    class Meta:
        model = Spice

class EggForm(ModelForm):
    class Meta:
        model = Egg
    spices = FieldList(FormField(SpiceForm))
```

I suggest modifying compare_faces to

    if not known_face_encodings:
        return []
    return list(_face_distance(known_face_encodings, face_encoding_to_check) <= tolerance)

to allow the user to input an empty list for known_face_encodings which then returns an empty list of "matches". Otherwise, an expected ValueError occurs which isn't particularly intuitive.

