I am not sure this is enough, because the new `@observe` will not work as expected with inheritance (independently of the question of the signature of the callback). In the following code, the handler in the derived class will not be called:

```Python
from traitlets import *

class Foo(HasTraits):
    
    bar = Int()
    
    @observe('bar')
    def handle_bar(self, change):
        print('base')
        
class Baz(Foo):
    
    def handler_bar(self, change):
        print('derived')

baz = Baz()
baz.bar = 1
```

While if you also decorate the derived class' method, you will get both 'base' and 'derived' printed... Hence, there is no natural way to reproduce the behavior of the `_bar_changed` handler.

The negative colors seems to be caused by this code

template <> inline void Structure :: Convert<char>   (char& dest,const FileDatabase& db) const
{
    // automatic rescaling from char to float and vice versa (seems useful for RGB colors)
    if (name == "float") {
        dest = static_cast<char>(db.reader->GetF4() * 255.f);
        return;
    }
    else if (name == "double") {
        dest = static_cast<char>(db.reader->GetF8() * 255.f);
        return;
    }
    ConvertDispatcher(dest,*this,db);
}


It is using char, when it should be unsigned char

